Waders feeding on the exposed mud at low tide.  There were curlews, many common redshank and other waders.  I was looking East and the Sun and distance made observation difficult.

Many thanks to Cedric Mroczko for putting me on the correct path to identifying the unknown calls as common redshank.


Original request:

I am fairly certain there is at least one curlew here, but what are the other calls?  One call type is a single or double note (is this also curlew?), the other a series of shorter notes in quick succession.  Many thanks for any advice with this.

recordings.rmk:
Recorded:

  • call, tuuu or tyuuu, at 0:00.3
  • display-flight song, tül-tül-tül-tuliiu-tuliiu-tuliiu..., at 0:01.6 and 0:10.2
  • call, teu-huhu, at 0:06.1 and 0:08.1

General observations: Pasture close to a shallow sea bay. A Common Redshank fly along the shoreline singing.

Recording remarks: According to NatureGuides (2020) a mate-call, tuuu, is made by the male to announce presence and to call up a mate. It is shorter than the main contnct call, which is spelled tyuuu, and are higher pitched. The call in this recording is 0,35 seconds long and at a slightly higher pitched (centered around 2.5 kHz) compared to the somewhat similar call of this recording: XC544135, which i 0,5 seconds long and centered around 2,2 kHz.

Other distinguishable species:

  • Common Chaffinch, Fringilla coelebs, call, fink!, at 0:06.7 (vaguely)
  • Eurasian Skylark, Alauda arvensis, song, at e.g. 0:07.3 (vaguely)
  • Mew Gull, Larus canus, long-call, kiä, at 0:09 (vaguely)

Sound classification and rendering: NatureGuides, 2020, Birds of Western Palearctic, AppStore; Svensson, Mullarney and Zetterström, 2009, Collins Bird Guide, Second Edition, HarperCollinsPublishers

Recording equipment: Dodotronic Hi-sound Stereo AOL Parabolic Microphone, Zoom H5 Recorder

Recorded:

  • alert call, tyuuuu, at 0:00.5, 0:06.6 and 0:46.4
  • call, teu-huhu, at 1:06.3 and 1:12.5
  • display-flight song, tül-tül-tül-tuliiu-tuliiu-tuliiu..., at 0:43.5 (bird in background)

General observations: Pasture close to a shallow sea bay. Two Common Redshanks are calling from the ground

Other distinguishable species:

  • Northern Lapwing, Vanellus vanellus, song, at 0:02.5 (vaguely)
  • Eurasian Skylark, Alauda arvensis, song, at e.g. 0:12.4
  • Black-headed Gull, Chroicocephalus ridibundus, call, krreearr, at 0:17.9
  • Great Spotted Woodpecker Dendrocopos major, drumming, at 1:11.8 (vaguely)

Sound classification and rendering: NatureGuides, 2020, Birds of Western Palearctic, AppStore

Recording equipment: Dodotronic Hi-sound Stereo AOL Parabolic Microphone, Zoom H5 Recorder
